<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>tough nut to crack • tough row to hoe</xh5><p> <i>tough nut to crack</i>—(also: hard nut to crack) 1. a difficult person to deal with: Meggie was going to be a <u>tough nut to crack</u> and he couldn’t afford to frighten her. 2. a difficult problem or task to undertake: Getting them all here on time will be a <u>tough nut to crack</u>.</p><p> <i>tough row to hoe</i>—(also: hard row to hoe) = tough nut to crack 2: Getting the contract signed is going to be a <u>tough row to hoe</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>tough act to follow</b>—(also: hard act to follow) used of an outstanding individual or a particularly good performance that will be difficult to emulate: The gifts, the decorations, the food—everything was exacting and amazing. It will be a <u>tough act to follow</u>.</p> </entry>
